1
00:00:02,480 --> 00:00:09,310
Our next guest on the Empowering Leaders podcast

2
00:00:09,310 --> 00:00:12,369
is Roger Gillespie, the founder of Baker's Delight.

3
00:00:12,509 --> 00:00:14,630
I love catching up with him in person

4
00:00:14,630 --> 00:00:17,510
and the strong sense of values comes through,

5
00:00:18,030 --> 00:00:19,730
his passion for ethical leadership

6
00:00:19,730 --> 00:00:22,850
and the idea that everyone in business should win,

7
00:00:22,910 --> 00:00:25,010
your suppliers, your customers, your partners.

8
00:00:25,710 --> 00:00:27,809
It's an incredible legacy that he has.

9
00:00:28,230 --> 00:00:29,250
Everyone wins.

10
00:00:29,410 --> 00:00:30,530
You stay in business longer.

11
00:00:30,530 --> 00:00:33,689
If there's a lopsided relationship, it doesn't work.

12
00:00:33,689 --> 00:00:36,130
Look, if you don't treat your wife well,

13
00:00:36,270 --> 00:00:37,189
she won't stay around.

14
00:00:37,689 --> 00:00:38,590
It's the same thing.

15
00:00:38,789 --> 00:00:40,649
You've got to have a win-win.

16
00:00:51,859 --> 00:00:55,920
Very closely aligned with the work that we're doing at Alita,

17
00:00:56,500 --> 00:00:58,759
where leaders are getting together to connect,

18
00:00:58,840 --> 00:00:59,759
to learn and to share

19
00:00:59,759 --> 00:01:02,679
and what we think is a life-changing opportunity.

20
00:01:03,259 --> 00:01:05,459
I hope you enjoy this chat with Roger Gillespie,

21
00:01:05,799 --> 00:01:08,040
the founder of Baker's Delight, as much as I did.

22
00:01:09,299 --> 00:01:12,120
Roger Gillespie is a fourth-generation baker.

23
00:01:12,540 --> 00:01:13,040
In 19...

24
00:01:13,260 --> 00:01:14,579
In 1980, he and his wife, Lesley,

25
00:01:14,640 --> 00:01:17,900
opened the first Baker's Delight in Melbourne's Glenferry Road, Hawthorne,

26
00:01:18,019 --> 00:01:19,659
with the aim of making enough money

27
00:01:19,659 --> 00:01:22,400
to be able to choose the schools they wanted their kids to attend.

28
00:01:22,959 --> 00:01:26,340
40 years later, Baker's Delight has over 700 stores

29
00:01:26,340 --> 00:01:28,719
across Australia, New Zealand and North America,

30
00:01:28,840 --> 00:01:32,159
becoming one of Australia's greatest-ever business success stories.

31
00:01:32,739 --> 00:01:34,159
Roger and his family are celebrated

32
00:01:34,159 --> 00:01:36,299
for their outstanding contribution and philanthropy,

33
00:01:36,900 --> 00:01:38,719
including the Prime Minister's Award for Excellence

34
00:01:38,719 --> 00:01:40,019
in Community Business Partnership

35
00:01:40,019 --> 00:01:42,700
for their work with the Breast Cancer Network Australia.

36
00:01:43,260 --> 00:01:45,959
They've raised over $20 million in the past 20 years.

37
00:01:46,400 --> 00:01:48,459
Roger, it's great to catch up with you in person.

38
00:01:48,560 --> 00:01:49,540
I really appreciate your time today.

39
00:01:50,000 --> 00:01:51,659
Well, it's a pleasure to be here, Luke,

40
00:01:51,700 --> 00:01:52,980
and thanks for the invitation.

41
00:01:53,280 --> 00:01:55,700
Can I go back to 1980 to start with...

42
00:01:55,700 --> 00:01:58,120
You opened that first store in Glenferry Road, Hawthorne.

43
00:01:58,719 --> 00:02:00,340
Could you believe 40 years later

44
00:02:00,340 --> 00:02:03,900
that you'd employ more than 15,000 people in a 700-store?

45
00:02:04,099 --> 00:02:05,459
I mean, was it even possible in your mind?

46
00:02:05,680 --> 00:02:09,699
It was possible, but it wasn't a dream at that point.

47
00:02:09,699 --> 00:02:13,080
People often say, well, where did you get the idea?

48
00:02:13,259 --> 00:02:14,780
Well, the idea just evolved.

49
00:02:14,919 --> 00:02:15,740
We had one store,

50
00:02:16,020 --> 00:02:18,039
and then there was another opportunity for another one,

51
00:02:18,080 --> 00:02:19,520
so we took it, another one, another one,

52
00:02:19,560 --> 00:02:22,000
and then a whole lot more people wanted to be part of it,

53
00:02:22,060 --> 00:02:23,060
so we just kept going.

54
00:02:23,539 --> 00:02:25,599
And I'm an addict, I should mention.

55
00:02:26,439 --> 00:02:28,020
I'll fess up straight away.

56
00:02:28,500 --> 00:02:30,159
I'm addicted to opening bakeries.

57
00:02:30,259 --> 00:02:32,400
If I don't open one for a month, I get the shakes,

58
00:02:32,539 --> 00:02:33,919
and I have to keep at it.

59
00:02:34,219 --> 00:02:35,500
Well, does that come from your dad?

60
00:02:35,759 --> 00:02:37,879
I'll jump into there, because there's a famous line,

61
00:02:37,879 --> 00:02:40,699
I think he said to you, you know, as a baker himself,

62
00:02:40,819 --> 00:02:42,159
people always want to eat bread.

63
00:02:42,280 --> 00:02:42,879
It was...

64
00:02:43,259 --> 00:02:44,439
Pretty reasonable thought, isn't it?

65
00:02:44,439 --> 00:02:44,979
Yeah, yeah.

66
00:02:45,120 --> 00:02:47,099
Well, and that's been true so far,

67
00:02:47,219 --> 00:02:48,500
and it's looking good for the future.

68
00:02:49,020 --> 00:02:50,900
You started with a business partner,

69
00:02:51,400 --> 00:02:53,139
a guy by the name of Gary Stevenson,

70
00:02:53,180 --> 00:02:55,620
and a handful of years in, you're buying him out.

71
00:02:55,759 --> 00:02:56,939
Can I ask you about that?

72
00:02:57,020 --> 00:02:58,439
Was that a difficult thing to do?

73
00:02:58,539 --> 00:03:01,039
And I suppose if you're Gary, does he look back and think,

74
00:03:01,120 --> 00:03:03,360
gee, I might have been well advised to hang around

75
00:03:03,360 --> 00:03:04,379
with Roger and Leslie?

76
00:03:04,580 --> 00:03:07,039
Yeah, well, sadly, we've lost contact with him,

77
00:03:07,039 --> 00:03:09,219
and I'd like to be able to catch up with him.

78
00:03:09,280 --> 00:03:11,840
I haven't seen him for, I'd say, 15 years.

79
00:03:11,939 --> 00:03:13,039
I think we had a celebration.

80
00:03:13,259 --> 00:03:16,580
We hit 25 years, and he came along to that.

81
00:03:17,139 --> 00:03:21,939
But he wanted to follow his dream and be in the IT world,

82
00:03:22,460 --> 00:03:26,199
so he'd had enough of bakeries, so he said,

83
00:03:26,280 --> 00:03:27,699
I want to get out, so we bought him out.

84
00:03:28,120 --> 00:03:30,919
There are lots of bakeries around the world, Roger.

85
00:03:31,039 --> 00:03:34,400
Why has Baker's Delight, in your mind, been such a success?

86
00:03:35,120 --> 00:03:38,099
Well, I think it comes from our actual name,

87
00:03:38,639 --> 00:03:42,099
which ironically we don't have the same name in Canada,

88
00:03:42,099 --> 00:03:43,099
but we...

89
00:03:43,460 --> 00:03:44,479
are equally successful.

90
00:03:45,159 --> 00:03:46,419
But we live to delight.

91
00:03:46,639 --> 00:03:49,379
You know, when we thought of the name, we said, well, we're bakers,

92
00:03:49,800 --> 00:03:51,639
and we want to delight every customer,

93
00:03:51,800 --> 00:03:53,620
and we want to be delighted as bakers

94
00:03:53,620 --> 00:03:55,360
when we pull a loaf of bread out of the oven.

95
00:03:55,479 --> 00:03:59,360
We want that delight to be felt in our own staff

96
00:03:59,360 --> 00:04:01,979
and then pass that delight on to every customer.

97
00:04:02,219 --> 00:04:05,099
And we still are true to that, to the name,

98
00:04:05,319 --> 00:04:09,180
and to ignite that passion for anyone who wants to join us.

99
00:04:09,180 --> 00:04:12,400
So when I used to recruit franchisees,

100
00:04:12,840 --> 00:04:13,240
I'd say,

101
00:04:13,259 --> 00:04:16,139
you have to be so enthusiastic about, you know,

102
00:04:16,180 --> 00:04:18,980
delighting every customer that you've got to walk through a brick wall

103
00:04:18,980 --> 00:04:23,240
and then crawl across broken glass if you want to be part of this business.

104
00:04:23,339 --> 00:04:24,839
That's how enthusiastic you have to be.

105
00:04:25,300 --> 00:04:26,699
And that's sort of instilled.

106
00:04:26,819 --> 00:04:29,279
It's part of our culture that you've got to be committed

107
00:04:29,279 --> 00:04:31,579
to delighting every customer every day.

108
00:04:32,139 --> 00:04:34,980
And it is the values that when you read about your history

109
00:04:34,980 --> 00:04:38,000
that you live and, you know, you train people and crew.

110
00:04:38,019 --> 00:04:40,720
And you're a great part of the communities that you live in.

111
00:04:40,720 --> 00:04:43,160
And all the stores are really attached to their...

112
00:04:43,160 --> 00:04:44,720
Can you kind of pick on what you said before?

113
00:04:44,819 --> 00:04:45,300
Because it's interesting.

114
00:04:45,379 --> 00:04:47,100
You think of this great brand now, Baker's Delight,

115
00:04:47,139 --> 00:04:49,699
and it's a brilliant name, and you live it with your values.

116
00:04:49,800 --> 00:04:52,980
But in Canada, where you're growing, you know, exponentially,

117
00:04:53,420 --> 00:04:54,180
it's Cobb's?

118
00:04:54,319 --> 00:04:55,240
It's Cobb's Bread, yeah.

119
00:04:55,300 --> 00:04:57,519
So why the change in that part of the world?

120
00:04:57,519 --> 00:05:00,839
Well, we tried to use Baker's Delight there.

121
00:05:00,920 --> 00:05:03,199
We got the lawyers to do a company search,

122
00:05:03,259 --> 00:05:05,160
and there was a company there called Bakery Delight,

123
00:05:05,319 --> 00:05:06,439
spelled slightly differently.

124
00:05:06,879 --> 00:05:08,819
And they sold muffin mix.

125
00:05:09,300 --> 00:05:13,120
And in Australia, we'd be able to sort of cohabitate using the brands,

126
00:05:13,199 --> 00:05:15,579
for different businesses, but we couldn't do it.

127
00:05:15,579 --> 00:05:18,259
So we asked them for permission and offered them some money.

128
00:05:19,579 --> 00:05:22,160
And they quickly turned to their lawyers

129
00:05:22,160 --> 00:05:24,639
and asked for 10 times more than what we'd offered them.

130
00:05:25,100 --> 00:05:27,639
And our offer was 100 grand, and they wanted a million.

131
00:05:27,839 --> 00:05:29,800
We didn't know whether we were going to succeed or not.

132
00:05:29,879 --> 00:05:32,920
So we said, well, we're opening them as company-owned bakeries,

133
00:05:32,980 --> 00:05:35,339
so they're company-owned bakeries, Cobb's.

134
00:05:36,379 --> 00:05:40,379
And then we discovered later that it also stands for Canada's Own Bread

135
00:05:40,379 --> 00:05:42,620
and a few other acronyms,

136
00:05:43,160 --> 00:05:44,160
Cunning Old Baker.

137
00:05:47,100 --> 00:05:50,720
And the same sort of design.

138
00:05:51,220 --> 00:05:55,819
People go into our Canadian stores and discuss it.

139
00:05:55,839 --> 00:05:57,500
This is a rip-off from Baker's Delight.

140
00:05:57,959 --> 00:06:00,459
And similarly, Canadians come to our store here and say,

141
00:06:00,519 --> 00:06:01,860
this is a rip-off of Cobb's Bread.

142
00:06:03,120 --> 00:06:07,279
So we talk about you and your values, which you're renowned for,

143
00:06:07,420 --> 00:06:11,600
and I read about you really obsessed with win-wins for your franchises.

144
00:06:11,600 --> 00:06:13,079
Is their success paramount to you?

145
00:06:13,079 --> 00:06:13,139
Yeah.

146
00:06:13,160 --> 00:06:18,079
Your ongoing success, and you talk about the loyalty to your suppliers.

147
00:06:18,220 --> 00:06:20,399
Some of them have been with you for decades and decades,

148
00:06:20,540 --> 00:06:21,560
and it's customer first.

149
00:06:21,740 --> 00:06:23,220
I love that message, Roger.

150
00:06:23,639 --> 00:06:27,399
In a world now where I feel like everyone in business is trying to get a win

151
00:06:27,399 --> 00:06:29,759
over someone else, or there's got to be a winner and a loser,

152
00:06:30,060 --> 00:06:32,259
can you explain why that's worked so well for you?

153
00:06:32,939 --> 00:06:37,759
It was â€“ I don't know when we first sort of realised that that's the way we work,

154
00:06:37,920 --> 00:06:41,879
but it's every relationship we have has to be a win-win.

155
00:06:42,120 --> 00:06:43,079
So whether it's a customer,

156
00:06:43,079 --> 00:06:44,500
whether it's a customer coming and getting love for bread,

157
00:06:44,579 --> 00:06:46,660
the customer has to be happy to pay whatever they pay

158
00:06:46,660 --> 00:06:49,519
to receive the product they love and enjoy.

159
00:06:50,379 --> 00:06:52,779
We have to be happy to pay for the price of flour.

160
00:06:52,899 --> 00:06:55,360
We have to be happy to pay certain rents.

161
00:06:55,779 --> 00:06:59,560
Sadly, that doesn't happen as often as it should, but it's getting better.

162
00:07:00,519 --> 00:07:02,259
So it's just everyone wins.

163
00:07:02,480 --> 00:07:03,600
You stay in business longer.

164
00:07:03,740 --> 00:07:06,759
If there's a lopsided relationship, it doesn't work.

165
00:07:07,379 --> 00:07:10,720
If you don't treat your wife well, she won't stay around.

166
00:07:11,100 --> 00:07:12,240
It's the same thing.

167
00:07:12,240 --> 00:07:17,060
you know, you've got to have a win-win. Everyone has to be happy, both sides of the equation. If

168
00:07:17,060 --> 00:07:20,720
you're not, it doesn't last. Simple as that. Well, it sounds like old-fashioned values,

169
00:07:20,860 --> 00:07:25,120
Roger, but when you think about it, it is good business, isn't it? And it's sustainable,

170
00:07:25,439 --> 00:07:29,300
and it's happier business, isn't it? And I mean, you know, you get a win over someone and they

171
00:07:29,300 --> 00:07:34,060
lose. I mean, I am a bit of a believer in the karmic cycle comes around eventually, isn't it?

172
00:07:34,060 --> 00:07:39,259
So having said that, I mean, it's not utopia, is it? I mean, you have people that don't work out,

173
00:07:39,259 --> 00:07:43,920
but franchisees that aren't up to it. And so I read some of your language there, and correct me

174
00:07:43,920 --> 00:07:48,620
if I'm wrong, hire slowly, fire quickly. So explain a bit more about why that's important to you.

175
00:07:48,920 --> 00:07:55,199
Well, if you've got an infection in your body, if you don't deal with it, you'll get sicker.

176
00:07:55,560 --> 00:08:00,279
So it's the same, you know, the old saying of a rotten apple in a case causes all the apples to

177
00:08:00,279 --> 00:08:06,399
go off. So you've really got to weed the garden regularly and get rid of the components that

178
00:08:06,399 --> 00:08:09,240
aren't working. If you don't do that, the...

179
00:08:09,240 --> 00:08:14,939
The negative drags down the positive and the whole thing goes pretty ugly. And we don't want that.

180
00:08:15,199 --> 00:08:19,180
So your instinct is when you get an instinct that someone's just not up to it,

181
00:08:19,259 --> 00:08:20,300
you really should act quickly.

182
00:08:20,439 --> 00:08:25,500
Yeah. Yeah. Have to. Yeah. And sadly, we don't always, but wherever we can, we do.

183
00:08:25,899 --> 00:08:31,660
I love self-made stories. And it's so brilliant to sit along across from you now to tell...

184
00:08:31,660 --> 00:08:36,139
To someone listening to this who wants to start, wants to have a go, has got an idea,

185
00:08:36,139 --> 00:08:38,200
what do you say to an aspiring entrepreneur?

186
00:08:39,240 --> 00:08:44,899
Be clear on what you're trying to achieve, get good people to help you, get good legal advice,

187
00:08:45,480 --> 00:08:50,100
but be committed, 100% committed, you know, walking through the brick wall and

188
00:08:50,100 --> 00:08:56,059
crawl across broken glass. It will be harder than you think, it will take longer than you think,

189
00:08:56,120 --> 00:09:01,539
and it will cost more than you think. So if you go in with your eyes open,

190
00:09:01,620 --> 00:09:05,899
realizing those three things, you're more likely to succeed. But if you're half-hearted,

191
00:09:05,899 --> 00:09:08,580
it won't work. You've got to be 100% committed,

192
00:09:09,240 --> 00:09:13,419
and really get other people supporting you, and get other people on board to

193
00:09:13,419 --> 00:09:15,940
celebrate your idea and make it happen with you.

194
00:09:16,200 --> 00:09:18,100
But genuinely have a go. I can see that in you.

195
00:09:18,100 --> 00:09:21,700
Exactly. If you don't have a go, you know, like your early career as a football player,

196
00:09:22,379 --> 00:09:27,960
18 men line up on each side, same weight, same, you know, but the ones who are more determined,

197
00:09:28,120 --> 00:09:32,879
more skilled, follow the coach, do the job properly, they come out the winner. Simple.

198
00:09:33,200 --> 00:09:38,679
That's how life works in almost every situation. Baker's Delight, Roger, is a genuine family

199
00:09:38,679 --> 00:09:39,019
business.

200
00:09:39,240 --> 00:09:43,279
It is you and Leslie who founded it, and now the succession planning, your daughter,

201
00:09:43,399 --> 00:09:47,779
Elise, her husband, David, are joint CEOs in this part of the world, and your son, Aaron,

202
00:09:47,860 --> 00:09:52,740
heads up the North American business. We all know families have ups and downs, businesses have ups

203
00:09:52,740 --> 00:09:57,559
and downs. How have you treaded that path so successfully to be able to manage, you know,

204
00:09:57,580 --> 00:10:02,539
family and siblings and kids working together, and you working with Leslie so effectively?

205
00:10:02,539 --> 00:10:09,059
Well, we started with the next generation 15 years ago. We had a fellow called Michael Andrew,

206
00:10:09,240 --> 00:10:15,720
who sadly passed away three years ago. He chaired our family council, which we set up about 15 years

207
00:10:15,720 --> 00:10:21,860
ago, and the kids weren't really interested at that point. All of them were working in Canada

208
00:10:21,860 --> 00:10:27,860
and living in Canada. Our daughter and her husband lived there for eight years, and they were working

209
00:10:27,860 --> 00:10:32,600
together, and they were working well, but Elise wanted to come back to Australia, and her husband's

210
00:10:32,600 --> 00:10:37,659
South African. He didn't care where he lived as long as he was with her. It's their 12th wedding

211
00:10:37,659 --> 00:10:38,840
anniversary today, by the way.

212
00:10:39,240 --> 00:10:45,799
But they, so they came along to this first meeting, and KPMG prepared a whole lot of information about,

213
00:10:45,879 --> 00:10:50,340
you know, where the assets were and blah, blah, blah. And then we had another meeting six months

214
00:10:50,340 --> 00:10:55,539
later, and then Michael said to them, well, remember the last meeting? And they all looked

215
00:10:55,539 --> 00:10:59,220
blankly and couldn't remember anything from the previous meeting. You know, the first couple of

216
00:10:59,220 --> 00:11:05,159
years, we'd meet twice a year, and then they suddenly became interested. Well, I say suddenly

217
00:11:05,159 --> 00:11:09,220
after two or three years, and they're more and more interested. Now we meet four times a year,

218
00:11:09,240 --> 00:11:15,580
as a family council, to look at our philanthropic interests as well as our business interests and try

219
00:11:15,580 --> 00:11:22,100
and look at Baker Slider's owners. So we just had a three-day retreat in Canada last month to do a

220
00:11:22,100 --> 00:11:26,500
sort of high-level review of where we want to go with the business and where we want to go with

221
00:11:26,500 --> 00:11:31,480
our other investments and our philanthropy. So it was fantastic. But if you don't do those,

222
00:11:31,879 --> 00:11:38,340
put in the time and start early, like the kids were in their 20s when we started. They're now

223
00:11:38,340 --> 00:11:39,220
both in their 40s.

224
00:11:39,240 --> 00:11:46,259
And it's working, I think, very well. You know, they've taken control. I'm chairman of the board.

225
00:11:46,580 --> 00:11:51,580
Leslie's on the board as well. We go to the office for other things. I'm going to office today for a

226
00:11:51,580 --> 00:11:55,480
separate meeting, nothing to do with Baker's Delight. And that's more often the reason I'm

227
00:11:55,480 --> 00:12:01,039
there for other things rather than Baker's Delight. So it's worked well. But get in early if you want

228
00:12:01,039 --> 00:12:07,740
to do succession plans. When we were in Canada, we also went to this business association meeting,

229
00:12:07,740 --> 00:12:09,200
so family business association.

230
00:12:09,240 --> 00:12:14,220
I don't know how often it happens, but it happened to be on where we were there and our son's on the

231
00:12:14,220 --> 00:12:19,240
board of it. So he said, come along. And amongst the various presenters, there were a whole lot of

